EXAM A — "From Today's Web to Tomorrow's Agents"
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
Narrative arc: present-day REST/hypermedia design → the historical road
not taken (Xanadu) → how those same ideas resurface at the cutting edge of
LLM/agent integration. The student builds up a vocabulary (HATEOAS,
addressable/stable references) in the first two questions that they must
then redeploy to evaluate a modern AI-systems design problem.

## A.1 [Easy — 100 points] — Hypermedia & REST APIs

In the lecture, you encountered **HATEOAS** (Hypermedia as the Engine of
Application State). Explain what HATEOAS means and why it is considered
part of REST's *uniform interface* constraint.

### Reference Solution

- **Definition:** HATEOAS means that a client interacts with an application
  purely through hypermedia (links, forms/affordances) that the server
  supplies dynamically inside each representation, rather than through
  prior, out-of-band knowledge of a fixed URI scheme.
- **Why it belongs to the uniform interface:** The uniform interface
  constraint requires (among other sub-constraints) that resources be
  manipulated through representations, that messages be self-descriptive,
  and that application state transitions be driven by hypermedia contained
  in those representations (HATEOAS). Together these sub-constraints ensure
  a client only needs a generic understanding of the media type and link
  semantics — not of the server's specific URI structure.
- **Consequence:** Servers can change URIs, workflows, or add new states
  without breaking clients, because clients follow links/affordances at
  runtime instead of hard-coding paths. This is what enables independent
  evolvability of client and server.
- Award full points for: correct definition + explicit link to uniform
  interface / self-descriptive messages + at least one consequence
  (decoupling / evolvability).

--------------------------------------------------------------------------

## A.2 [Medium — 200 points] — History of Hypertext & the Web (Xanadu)

"Immutable versioning and addressable spans give transclusion referential
guarantees that the Web cannot natively provide."

a) Explain how addressable spans and immutability jointly enable stable,
verifiable references. b) Explain why the WWW's architecture leads to
"link rot" and content drift. c) Give one concrete real-world example of
link rot or content drift, and explain what a Xanadu-style addressing
scheme would have prevented in that example.

### Reference Solution

a) **Addressable spans + immutability:** transclusion requires that
*specific portions* of a document (byte spans), not just whole documents,
be addressable, so that precise fragments can be reused/cited. Immutable
versioning guarantees that once a version of a document is created, it
never changes — so a reference to a given span of a given version remains
stable and verifiable forever; content integrity can be checked because
the referenced bytes cannot silently change under the reference.

b) **Why the Web is unstable:** the WWW addresses resources by *location*
(URLs) rather than by content or fixed version, and resources are
mutable — the same URL can be edited, replaced, or removed at any time.
There is also no native mechanism for stable *fragment* identifiers tied
to immutable versions. This causes "link rot" (URLs stop resolving) and
"content drift" (the URL still resolves, but to different content than
what was originally referenced).

c) **Example:** a citation in an academic paper or news article links to
a web page that is later edited (the argument being cited is changed or
removed) or taken offline entirely (404). A Xanadu-style scheme —
addressing an immutable version and byte span rather than a mutable
location — would have kept the exact cited content permanently
retrievable and unchanged, regardless of what happens to the "current"
page at that location.

- Grading: 2 pts each for (a) and (b) if clearly explained and connected
  to transclusion/integrity respectively (partial credit for
  vague/incomplete answers); 2 pts for a concrete, well-connected example
  in (c).

